Please plan a new feature, using this OCR Research. Of course, some syntax may be off, due to being all in one stream of text, but the concepts are the guide.
====================

User prompt 1 of 4 - 6/16/2026, 8:30:03 PM:
I need an open-source solution to have Android camera based OCR to feed text-to-speech in my accessibility app in development.  The app would need to help a totally blind person read printed materials.

GPT-5 mini:
**Planning actionable solutions**

I’m thinking we need to offer a structured and actionable solution. This involves focusing on real-world facts. To achieve that, I'll need to use the WebSearch tool as per the established rules. It seems essential to also invoke RelatedSearchTerms at the end to enhance our findings. Overall, I’m just trying to ensure the process is clear and meets the guidelines while being comprehensive!**Considering tools for implementation**

I need to cite sources when using WebSearch. I’ll recommend the stack including PaddleOCR via ONNX Runtime Mobile or Tesseract, along with Android TTS. 

For accessibility, I should integrate with TalkBack and consider using CameraX for stable capture. I'll outline implementation steps and ensure to include citations. 

Then, I’ll call the RelatedSearchTerms tool at the end. I need to craft a concise answer with appropriate headings and format it clearly.Recommended open-source stack (offline, high-accuracy):

- OCR engine (best accuracy/balance):
  - PaddleOCR models converted to ONNX and run with ONNX Runtime Mobile on Android — good accuracy for printed text, handles rotation/layout better than Tesseract. <citation src="2"></citation>
- Lightweight alternative (simpler, widely used):
  - Tesseract (v4/5) via Tesseract4Android / tess-two — mature, CPU-first, good for printed text and many languages; available on F‑Droid. <citation src="5,3"></citation>
- Camera capture:
  - Android CameraX for stable live camera feed and image preprocessing (auto-focus, exposure, resolution control). <citation src="4"></citation>
- TTS (open-source / on-device):
  - Android TextToSpeech (system TTS) for best integration; or eSpeak NG / Pico TTS builds if you need fully open-source voices offline.
- Optional runtime / ML infra:
  - ONNX Runtime Mobile for running converted PaddleOCR models on-device. <citation src="2,3"></citation>

Minimal implementation plan (prescriptive):

1. Capture:
   - Use CameraX Preview + ImageAnalysis to stream frames; downsample to ~1080p and run prefilters (grayscale, contrast, denoise). Use auto-capture on steady frame detection (motion low + focus locked).
   - Rotate/deskew using EXIF or detect orientation with a small angle classifier.

2. Text detection + recognition:
   - Option A (recommended): Run PaddleOCR pipeline (DB detector → angle classifier → recognizer) exported to ONNX and infer with ONNX Runtime Mobile. Postprocess with CTC decode and polygon-to-bbox cropping for lines. <citation src="2,3"></citation>
   - Option B: Run Tesseract (tessdata language packs) on cropped/deskewed images for simpler integration. <citation src="5,3"></citation>

3. Post-processing:
   - Group lines into logical reading order (top→bottom, left→right), merge small fragments, apply simple language-model spell-correction (optional) to improve TTS quality.

4. TTS output:
   - Feed cleaned text to Android TextToSpeech for immediate, accessible reading controls (rate, pitch). If you prefer OSS voices, integrate eSpeak NG native library and call it from JNI.

5. Accessibility UX:
   - Design gesture-based controls (start/stop scanning, read next line, repeat) and expose content descriptions so TalkBack users can get UI feedback.
   - Provide continuous-mode where OCR runs and announces new lines only when confidence > threshold and stable across N frames to avoid chatter.

6. Offline language packs & size:
   - Bundle only required language models (tessdata or PaddleOCR recognizer files) or download them on demand to keep APK size reasonable. Test memory/CPU on target devices.

7. Performance & accuracy tips:
   - Ensure 16–24 pixels per character height in the captured image.
   - Good lighting, high contrast, and minimal motion blur matter more than model complexity.
   - Use small ROI (region of interest) selection to limit work and improve speed.

Useful open-source starting points / codebases:
- Example: ONNX/Android port of Paddle-style OCR used in open apps — demonstrates exporting detector/recognizer to ONNX and Kotlin preprocessing. <citation src="2"></citation>
- Tesseract Android apps and libraries (Tesseract4Android / tess-two) and F‑Droid OCR app examples. <citation src="5,3"></citation>
- Google ML Kit guide for CameraX + text recognition (if you decide closed/Google option during prototyping). <citation src="4"></citation>

Next steps I can do for you (pick one):
- Provide a minimal CameraX + ONNX Runtime Mobile sample (Kotlin) that runs an ONNX recognizer on live frames.
- Provide a CameraX + Tesseract (tess-two) sample with TextToSpeech integration.
- Sketch the accessibility gesture/UX flows for blind users.

Which of those would you like me to produce?

--------------------

User prompt 2 of 4 - 6/16/2026, 8:32:26 PM:
I am already using installed voice engines. The rest will be controlled by an existing sppech-to-text command system. So provide 1 and 2.

GPT-5 mini:
Below are two concise, ready-to-adapt Kotlin samples you can drop into an Android app. Each captures frames with CameraX ImageAnalysis, does minimal preprocessing, and returns recognized text via a callback so your existing voice/command system can handle speaking/commands.

Important: add CAMERA and any storage permissions as needed. Replace model paths / tessdata paths with where you bundle or download them.

1) CameraX + ONNX Runtime Mobile (Paddle-style recognizer via ONNX)
- Gradle (app/build.gradle) essentials:
```gradle
dependencies {
  implementation "androidx.camera:camera-core:1.2.3"
  implementation "androidx.camera:camera-camera2:1.2.3"
  implementation "androidx.camera:camera-lifecycle:1.2.3"
  implementation "org.jetbrains:onnxruntime-mobile:1.15.1" // adjust version
  implementation "org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-coroutines-android:1.7.0"
}
```

- Kotlin: CameraX + ONNX inference (simplified)
```kotlin
// ONNXCameraOcr.kt
import android.content.Context
import android.graphics.Bitmap
import android.media.Image
import androidx.camera.core.ImageAnalysis
import androidx.camera.core.ImageProxy
import androidx.camera.lifecycle.ProcessCameraProvider
import androidx.core.content.ContextCompat
import kotlinx.coroutines.*
import ai.onnxruntime.OnnxTensor
import ai.onnxruntime.OrtEnvironment
import ai.onnxruntime.OrtSession
import java.nio.FloatBuffer

class ONNXCameraOcr(
  private val context: Context,
  private val lifecycleOwner: androidx.lifecycle.LifecycleOwner,
  private val modelPath: String, // e.g., "models/ocr_recognizer.onnx" in app files
  private val onText: (String) -> Unit
) {
  private val scope = CoroutineScope(Dispatchers.Default + SupervisorJob())
  private val env = OrtEnvironment.getEnvironment()
  private val session: OrtSession by lazy { env.createSession(modelPath, OrtSession.SessionOptions()) }

  fun start() {
    val cameraProviderFuture = ProcessCameraProvider.getInstance(context)
    cameraProviderFuture.addListener({
      val cameraProvider = cameraProviderFuture.get()
      val analyzer = ImageAnalysis.Builder()
        .setBackpressureStrategy(ImageAnalysis.STRATEGY_KEEP_ONLY_LATEST)
        .build()
      analyzer.setAnalyzer(ContextCompat.getMainExecutor(context), { image -> analyzeImage(image) })
      val cameraSelector = androidx.camera.core.CameraSelector.DEFAULT_BACK_CAMERA
      cameraProvider.unbindAll()
      cameraProvider.bindToLifecycle(lifecycleOwner, cameraSelector, analyzer)
    }, ContextCompat.getMainExecutor(context))
  }

  private fun analyzeImage(imageProxy: ImageProxy) {
    val mediaImage = imageProxy.image
    if (mediaImage != null) {
      scope.launch {
        try {
          val bitmap = yuvToBitmap(mediaImage, imageProxy.imageInfo.rotationDegrees)
          val inputTensor = preprocessForRecognizer(bitmap) // float32 normalized tensor
          val ortTensor = OnnxTensor.createTensor(env, inputTensor, longArrayOf(1, /*C*/3, /*H*/32, /*W*/inputTensorWidth))
          val outputs = session.run(mapOf(session.inputNames.iterator().next() to ortTensor))
          val raw = outputs[0].value as Array<FloatArray> // adjust depending on model
          val text = ctcDecode(raw)
          withContext(Dispatchers.Main) { onText(text) }
        } catch (e: Exception) {
          // handle
        } finally {
          imageProxy.close()
        }
      }
    } else {
      imageProxy.close()
    }
  }

  // Helpers (implementations simplified; adapt for your model shapes)
  private val inputTensorWidth = 320 // example; depends on recognizer
  private fun preprocessForRecognizer(bitmap: Bitmap): FloatBuffer {
    // Resize to recognizer height (e.g., 32) and width, normalize to [0,1] or [-1,1] as model requires
    val resized = Bitmap.createScaledBitmap(bitmap, inputTensorWidth, 32, true)
    val floatCount = 3 * 32 * inputTensorWidth
    val fb = FloatArray(floatCount)
    var idx = 0
    val pixels = IntArray(32 * inputTensorWidth)
    resized.getPixels(pixels, 0, inputTensorWidth, 0, 0, inputTensorWidth, 32)
    for (p in pixels) {
      val r = ((p shr 16) and 0xFF) / 255.0f
      val g = ((p shr 8) and 0xFF) / 255.0f
      val b = (p and 0xFF) / 255.0f
      fb[idx++] = r
      fb[idx++] = g
      fb[idx++] = b
    }
    return FloatBuffer.wrap(fb)
  }

  private fun ctcDecode(modelOutput: Array<FloatArray>): String {
    // Simple greedy CTC decode; map indices to chars via your label map
    val labelMap = loadLabelMap() // implement to return List<String> where index->char
    val sb = StringBuilder()
    var prev = -1
    for (t in modelOutput.indices) {
      val row = modelOutput[t]
      var maxIdx = 0
      var maxV = row[0]
      for (i in 1 until row.size) if (row[i] > maxV) { maxV = row[i]; maxIdx = i }
      if (maxIdx != prev && maxIdx != blankIndex()) sb.append(labelMap[maxIdx])
      prev = maxIdx
    }
    return sb.toString()
  }

  private fun blankIndex() = 0 // adjust if blank token index differs

  private fun yuvToBitmap(image: Image, rotationDegrees: Int): Bitmap {
    // Use ScriptIntrinsicYuvToRGB or ImageConverter utilities — implement efficient conversion.
    // For brevity, assume you implement a utility that returns properly rotated bitmap.
    TODO("Implement YUV -> Bitmap conversion and rotation")
  }

  fun stop() {
    scope.cancel()
    session.close()
    env.close()
  }
}
```
Notes:
- Export your detector/recognizer to ONNX. For best accuracy you typically run a detector (DB) to crop text regions, then the recognizer ONNX on each crop. For simple line OCR you can skip detector and run recognizer on ROI.
- Adjust tensor shape, normalization, and decoding for your specific model.
- Use a simple detector model or OpenCV contour detection to limit recognizer runs to probable text regions (improves speed).

2) CameraX + Tesseract (tess-two) — simpler integration
- Gradle (app/build.gradle):
```gradle
dependencies {
  implementation "androidx.camera:camera-core:1.2.3"
  implementation "androidx.camera:camera-camera2:1.2.3"
  implementation "androidx.camera:camera-lifecycle:1.2.3"
  implementation 'com.googlecode.tesseract.android:tess-two:9.1.0' // check latest
  implementation "org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-coroutines-android:1.7.0"
}
```

- Kotlin: CameraX + TessBaseAPI
```kotlin
// TessCameraOcr.kt
import android.content.Context
import android.graphics.Bitmap
import androidx.camera.core.ImageAnalysis
import androidx.camera.core.ImageProxy
import androidx.camera.lifecycle.ProcessCameraProvider
import androidx.core.content.ContextCompat
import kotlinx.coroutines.*
import com.googlecode.tesseract.android.TessBaseAPI
import java.io.File

class TessCameraOcr(
  private val context: Context,
  private val lifecycleOwner: androidx.lifecycle.LifecycleOwner,
  private val tessDataPath: String, // directory containing "tessdata" folder
  private val lang: String = "eng",
  private val onText: (String) -> Unit
) {
  private val scope = CoroutineScope(Dispatchers.Default + SupervisorJob())
  private val tess = TessBaseAPI()

  init {
    tess.init(tessDataPath, lang)
    tess.pageSegMode = TessBaseAPI.PageSegMode.PSM_AUTO
  }

  fun start() {
    val cameraProviderFuture = ProcessCameraProvider.getInstance(context)
    cameraProviderFuture.addListener({
      val cameraProvider = cameraProviderFuture.get()
      val analyzer = ImageAnalysis.Builder()
        .setBackpressureStrategy(ImageAnalysis.STRATEGY_KEEP_ONLY_LATEST)
        .build()
      analyzer.setAnalyzer(ContextCompat.getMainExecutor(context)) { image -> analyze(image) }
      val cameraSelector = androidx.camera.core.CameraSelector.DEFAULT_BACK_CAMERA
      cameraProvider.unbindAll()
      cameraProvider.bindToLifecycle(lifecycleOwner, cameraSelector, analyzer)
    }, ContextCompat.getMainExecutor(context))
  }

  private fun analyze(imageProxy: ImageProxy) {
    val mediaImage = imageProxy.image
    if (mediaImage != null) {
      scope.launch {
        try {
          val bitmap = yuvToBitmap(mediaImage, imageProxy.imageInfo.rotationDegrees)
          val gray = toGrayscaleAndBinarize(bitmap) // optional prep to improve accuracy
          tess.setImage(gray)
          val text = tess.utF8Text ?: ""
          withContext(Dispatchers.Main) { if (text.isNotBlank()) onText(text) }
        } catch (_: Exception) {
        } finally {
          imageProxy.close()
        }
      }
    } else imageProxy.close()
  }

  private fun toGrayscaleAndBinarize(src: Bitmap): Bitmap {
    // optional: convert to grayscale, apply threshold/adaptive threshold using OpenCV or simple filter
    return src
  }

  private fun yuvToBitmap(image: android.media.Image, rotationDegrees: Int): Bitmap {
    // Implement conversion or reuse utility; return rotated bitmap
    TODO("Implement YUV -> Bitmap conversion and rotation")
  }

  fun stop() {
    scope.cancel()
    tess.end()
  }
}
```
Notes:
- Put tessdata (traineddata files) in tessDataPath/tessdata/eng.traineddata. You can download compressed language packs and bundle selectively or download at first run to reduce APK size.
- Set tess.pageSegMode for your use case (PSM_SINGLE_BLOCK, PSM_SINGLE_LINE, etc.) for better results.
- Binarization and deskewing before tess.setImage greatly improves accuracy.

Practical tips to integrate these with your existing voice/command system
- Both classes use onText callback; send recognized string to your command handler.
- Debounce outputs: only forward lines when stable across N frames or when confidence above a threshold.
- For long documents, detect line/paragraph boundaries and let commands fetch “next”, “repeat”, or “spell” based on spoken commands.

If you want, I can:
- Provide a concrete YUV->Bitmap conversion utility (fast ScriptIntrinsicYuvToRGB) and a small detector example (OpenCV or simple MSER) to crop text regions; or
- Produce a complete minimal Android Studio sample project (Kotlin) for one of the two approaches.

Which helper would you like next?

